<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-22T18:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-22T18:30:00-05:00" n="521" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d521">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">831.24/77: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Corrigan</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-22T19:00:00-04:30">December 22, 1941—7
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>322. My No. 301, December 13, 2 p.m. President Medina called me to
                            Miraflores today to request my aid in obtaining immediate despatch of
                            airplanes and anti-aircraft guns and material which are urgently needed
                            to ward off attack which may be made on oil installations and airports.
                            He is convinced of the real danger of such attack and that it must be
                            anticipated. He stated that he has sufficient trained personnel if they
                            can be supplied with equipment.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Corrigan</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>